  "prompt": "What's the size of a 4K image?",
  "response": "A 4K image, often referred to in the context of 4K resolution for displays and televisions, typically has a resolution of 3840 x 2160 pixels. This resolution is also known as Ultra High Definition (UHD) or 2160p. \n\nHere are some key points about the size of a 4K image:\n\n1. **Resolution**: 3840 pixels wide by 2160 pixels tall.\n2. **Aspect Ratio**: The aspect ratio of a 4K image is 16:9, which is the standard for most modern televisions and monitors.\n3. **File Size**: The actual file size of a 4K image depends on the file format and compression used. For example:\n   - **Uncompressed 24-bit PNG**: Approximately 24.7 MB (3840 * 2160 * 3 bytes per pixel).\n   - **JPEG**: Can vary significantly based on compression level, but typically ranges from 1 MB to 10 MB.\n   - **TIFF**: Uncompressed TIFF files can be around 24.7 MB, similar to PNG.\n\n4. **Display Size**: The physical size of a 4K image on a screen depends on the pixel density (PPI) of the display. For example, on a 55-inch 4K TV, the image would span the entire screen.\n\nIn summary, a 4K image has a resolution of 3840 x 2160 pixels, and its file size can vary based on the format and compression used.",
